PARTS

2 versions of the top box:
-one simple, easy print
-one with the "RAMPS" text, bridge challenge

NOTE

Please note that there is a support part for the bottom box, show in red here

MOUNTING TIPS

you should mount it in this order:

1 - remove the support part
2 - set the rods mounts if you print this version (mount it directly on the printer or set only the 2 X-rods now and mount it on the printer at last moment)
3 - set the arduino (without the shield), insert the back of the arduino in the supported slot and push it onto the holes mounts.
4 - set the front face. At that moment the arduino should not move anymore.
5 - set the reset button into his hole.
6 - carefully plug the ramps on the arduino.
7 - set the fan and the fan filter on the back face.
8 - get all your cables throught the back face and set the back face in place.
9 - plug all the cables, insert nuts into there slots and close the case.

Oh yes! A near complete redesign of the infamous Butter Pig by steveweber314. Coincidentally, I see Steve on a regular basis so he's witnessed the transformation and additions I've included in the design.

Here are some highlights:

  • Fits a full stick of butter!
  • Prints with far less support
  • Tighter tolerances for improved butter containment
  • Dies are slimmer and can print laying down
  • New Corncob die
  • Introduction of the knoll shelf

Doesn't Matter

The body and butt require support. Screw the tail several times to help smooth wall and pusher imperfections. It's much tighter than the original to prevent butter blow-by.

I've printed several in both PLA & ABS. Obviously, being this is in contact with food you should consider using food-grade plastics. The one featured above uses some eSUN, SeeMeCNC and Fillamentum filaments.

One of the items that bugged me the most about the original design was how much space it takes up when it's full. By designing a shelf to put the pig on (and hold the dies) extends overall fridge space and keeps everything tidy. I recommend using alcohol to clean the wall of the fridge where you plan to mount the shelf. The bathroom 3M command strips work great. You can use a single long one or several small ones like below.

Ready for mounting Holder mounted The shelf can be removed and carried with the pig or left in place for storage. Look, Steve, the tail isn't in the way!!
If you color layer the tail in 15mm segments it can be treated as tablespoons. In Simplify3D I stop the first layer at 10mm, then alternate colors every 15mm (the last segment will be slightly more)

This is the base project for the OpenForge Wall Construction Kit. This project only contains the bases (stone and plain) that are used in the construction kit for building wall tiles. This project will be updated as new basic styles of walls and floors become available.

Select a base, then follow the links below to choose a floor style and a wall style. Prime, paint, (add magnets and filament rivets if you like) and glue.

There are a number of things I'm trying to solve with this moving forward.

1) There's practically a cambrian explosion of openforge pieces. to make all the possible combinations people might want, it results in potentially endless variety. Now if you want something that is a bit more of a special combination, or an odd size, it's easy to put together.
2) For some tiles, tudor especially, painting them in full tile form turned out to be a real pain. Now with this, you can print the tile, paint it and then assemble. This makes it much easier to reach awkward places on the parts.

For instructions on how to get started with OpenForge, take a look at our tutorials.

OpenForge is now a patron supported project. I use the resources that my patrons give me in order to get the resources to let me create more sophisticated tiles with a greater level of detail. Please, support me, and I’ll deliver an ongoing stream of awesome gaming terrain. You can find more about OpenForge and Masterwork Tools at our:

  • Online catalog and backer site
  • Website
  • Forums (Mostly we use facebook now)
  • Twitter
  • Facebook

Pre-assembly tips

1) most printers on the first layer will create a slight lip as the plastic is squeezed on the first layer. You will want to use a razor to cut that off from both the floor tile and the wall or else it can create a small gap.
2) I find painting the tiles as pieces much faster then doing it post assembly. I prime them as parts, paint them as parts and only after that do I glue the piece together.
3) Make batches of bases. I find printing, painting and assembling floor tiles + floor bases in batches and assembling those without a wall back really useful. They tend to be faster to paint and print then the backs, so it's easy to have a pile ready as I make new backs to go on them.

Assembly

1) put magnets in the base. You won't need them on one side for this step (where the wall will be)
2) glue the floor to the base, using the wall to space it appropriately. I use cyanoacrylate glue (syuperglue)
3) clamp
4) in a few minutes, unclamp and add the last set of magnets and then the back, gluing on the bottom and where it meets the floor.
5) reclamp

description.text:
*Update, I have printed the 21mm version... and it was scary strong using PETG.

Sometimes the simplest creations are the most useful. I was building a water-cooled PC and needed hose clamps, and was shocked to see average prices of around $10 for a pack of 10 and no designs online! This water clamp that I have designed will work from 10mm upwards, although the 10mm & 11mm clamps are pushing the limit of a 0.4 nozzle printing small teeth.

I have designed this piece to look attractive when placed on a water-block or in plain sight, therefore it is much more narrow than the nylon clamps you will buy in stores.

Careful considerations: Your choice of plastic is important if you will be using this on high heat applications, if you are planning to just sort wires then pla should be fine, but for watercooling or perhaps even car radiator hoses I recommend PETG or nylon.

For Watercooling using 3/8in. tubing use the 11mm size. (test pending)
For Watercooling using 7/16in. tubing use the 16mm size. (test pending)

*If using this on high heat or water sensitive applications, I can accept no responsibility for the structure of this creation... that will have to fall on you and the quality of your print/materials.

description.text:
Cam style clips for the HICTOP printer to Zip tie cabling to.

I made it thicker to make it stronger.

To install clip, insert cam into slot on bar and pull the outer tabs slightly while rotating clockwise. If you lift too hard on outer tabs you will break the cam off. Lift the tabs just enough to get them over the rail. The slit in the middle of the clip will flex and allow the locks to slip over the bar into the slot with the cam twisting into place. The clip will still slide left and right; if you position them where you need them and only tie the cables down after you have them positioned, your cables and clips will stay where you put them.

This is the kit I purchased from Harbor Fright to remove the fill material from the zip tie holes. http://www.harborfreight.com/56-piece-precision-knife-set-36410.html

remixed_from.title: Threadless Ball Screw. No More Backlash

description.text:
Just another 'threadless ballscrew' 3D-printed... What I really wanted to figure out is this: How much slip does this ballscrew accumulates when travelling over the smooth rods, moving around back and forth a couple times...? Is it suitable for an open-loop design, or do you need position sensors for feedback..? Backlash is very low, which is nice. The essential geometry of the tilted bearings was done in OpenScad, nice and customizable. The roller bearings push flat on the shaft surface. The script is a remix from: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:124706/#files
Thanks for that one! The part from OpenScad was then further edited in tinkercad to add fastening screws, double sides, and more details: https://tinkercad.com/things/73GGA5MH9z7 3D-printed and CNC-machined at FabLab Zurich:
http://www.zurich.fablab.ch See the parts moving: https://vimeo.com/76689145
This is still work in progress... But as for now: I got the final position after the test run in the video pretty accurate ~0.1mm (sorry, you can't check the scale), but if a disturbing force is applied during the movement, the ballscrew slips and things gets out of track very quickly. At the moment, I do not see a chance for open-loop control to function reliable. Has anyone else gone this way with success? I am very interested if anyone else could share test results of their builds! Future work:
  • Add springs to the fasterner screws
  • Clean up OpenScad script
  • Build this part from aluminium?
  • ...

  • 6x M5 Screws 20mm, and nuts for Bearings
  • 6x Flat washers M5
  • 2x M5 Screws 25mm for fastener

'Skull and Rattily Bones' is a small square section skull with intersecting X-Bones that are free to move within the skull... so they rattle!

No support is required and most well set up machines should print this with no issues. The bones should be free (as an "X") straight off the build plate.

If for some reason your machine / slicing app has caused your print to come out with the bones / skull stuck together check your bridging settings, Make sure you print at 0.20mm resolution (as this file is set to bridge effectively at that thickness layer), and if necessary increase the Z-Scale by 3-5% to increase the clearances. .

Great little gifts and fun around Halloween time.

Build your own 13dbi Dual BiQuad Antenna for 1.2-1.3Ghz Frequency.
This Antenna is linear polarized and will work great with your 1.2 - 1.3Ghz FPV Model.
Tested to a range of 50+km. This is an adaptation of the original BiQuad Design posted on RCGroups by Alex, aka IBCrazy.

Select the template you would like to use (sharp corners or round) and whether you want to print it directly with the spacers or rather glue them on later (makes it a bit easier to get it all lined up as the spacer does not get in the way).

In addition you need:
1 sheet of sheet metal (thickness doesn’t matter much. E.g. 26 gauge galvanized steel or a copper PCB board) - dimensions: 9.17”/23.28cm x 18.34”/46.56cm (if it is a bit off it is not to dramatic. Make sure that it at least covers the full area of the printed part)
1 coaxial cable (e.g. RG58/U)
1 length of solid 1.5mm copper wire

Tools:
Tape measure
Soldering iron
Solder
Calipers (optional)
Drill

How to put it together:

print the template and bend the copper wire and press it into the groove inside the template. This will take care of the right length and shape.
The wire is placed inside the template in one piece. The center top is bend and the 2 ends meet in the middle from the bottom left and right.
For the double biquad start in the middle and follow the grove all the way, only bend the wire at the end points and not at the 2 outer cross sections. Make sure that the wires do not touch at the intersection points (you could pull a small heat shrink tube over it or bend and place a drop of hot glue in between to keep the wires separated). The the picture for more info.

Finally follow the same instructions as for the BiQuad antenna here to finish it off (use the printed spacers instead of the nylon bolts): http://www.rcgroups.com/forums/showthread.php?t=1328260

Have fun and fly safe.

comments.text: I replaced my existing fan duct with this one because the airflow didn't work out as I expected. This fan duct turned out to work well but only with a 40x40x20mm fan. A 40x40x10mm fan wasn't strong enough to cool down the filament properly. There is something else that didn't work out aswell. The mounting for the fan is parallel to the heatbed. It would be better to have the fan mounted in 30° inclination. It would improve the airflow. At the moment the air is directly crashing into the frame of the fan and is cooling the fan duct frame instead of the filament. A 30° inclination mounting for the 40mm fan would improve this. An other thing is that the output is thin and wide. The cool air isn't cooling down the filament properly. It would be better to thicken and narrow the output. Beside that it's a really good fan duct!
